{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17565771","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17565771"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:31:57+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:31:57+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18454"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18454","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18454"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.07,0.32,0.28,0.29]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11183"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74877"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11183","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11183"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18454"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60383"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"27"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"1142"},{"type":"tags","id":"11194"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25939"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33415"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74877","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74877"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-month history of progressive nasal congestion, sneezing, and wheeze. Her symptoms are worse during the weekdays and improved when she went on holiday in Queensland. She works in a children\u0027s toy store.  She has eczema which is well managed with moderate strength topical steroids creams. She reports mild itching and swollen lips after helping prepare for the parties with collecting the signs and preparing the balloon garlands. She has recently noticed itching in her mouth after eating strawberries.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is bilateral nasal congestion with clear rhinorrhoea. Chest examination reveals mild wheeze throughout both lung fields.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Food allergy","Contact dermatitis","Allergic rhinitis","Latex allergy","Occupational asthma"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case presents classic features of \u003Cstrong\u003Elatex allergy\u003C/strong\u003E. The key features supporting this diagnosis are the temporal relationship between symptoms and workplace exposure (balloons and likely rubber kid toys), concurrent contact symptoms with latex products, and possible cross-reactivity with fruits (latex-fruit syndrome).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOccupational asthma\u003C/strong\u003E is closely related but typically refers to respiratory symptoms caused by workplace sensitizers. While this patient has respiratory symptoms, the presence of contact symptoms and oral allergy syndrome suggests a more systemic latex allergy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAllergic rhinitis\u003C/strong\u003E could explain the nasal symptoms but would not account for the contact symptoms with latex products or the oral symptoms with fruits. The clear temporal relationship with latex exposure makes isolated allergic rhinitis less likely.  The cessation of symptoms on travelling north is likely to be lack of occupational exposure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EContact dermatitis\u003C/strong\u003E is a Type IV delayed hypersensitivity reaction that could explain skin symptoms from latex exposure, but would not account for the immediate respiratory symptoms or oral allergy syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFood allergy\u003C/strong\u003E alone would not explain the work-related pattern of symptoms or the reaction to latex products. The oral symptoms with fruits are more likely related to cross-reactivity with latex proteins.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELatex allergy is a Type I (immediate) hypersensitivity reaction mediated by IgE antibodies. It is an important consideration for health care professionals as well with exosure to latex materials though less so now that latex-free synthetics are more common.  Workers with frequent exposure to latex products are at increased risk. The latex-fruit syndrome occurs due to cross-reactive proteins present in both latex and certain foods, particularly banana, avocado, tomato and kiwi. Management involves latex avoidance and may require a change in work practices or environment.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Type I hypersensitivity reactions to latex commonly present with respiratory symptoms including rhinitis and bronchospasm.","Workers with occupational exposure to latex products are at increased risk of latex allergy.","Cross-reactivity between latex and certain foods (especially banana, avocado, and kiwi) is well-documented."],"references":["Australian Society of Clinical Immunology and Allergy (ASICA). Latex Allergy Frequently Asked Questions. ASICA. 2024.  Available at: https://www.allergy.org.au/patients/other-allergy/latex-allergy","naphylaxis Caused by Occupational Exposure to Balloons. Cureus. 2022 Jun 12;14(6).  Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC9275731/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60383"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18454"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60383","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60383"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-28T02:31:17+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-28T02:32:37+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11183"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74877"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"27","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/27"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc77","name":"Occupational/Environmental Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"descr